{{refimprove|date=March 2016}} {{Infobox ethnic group | group = Punjabi Canadian | image = | population = '''545,730''' (2011)<ref>{{cite web|title=NHS Profile, Canada, 2011, Census Data|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Data=Count&SearchText=canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=Non-official%20language&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1|website=Government of Canada, Statistics Canada|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref><ref group="lower-alpha">(Only includes the number of native [[Punjabi language]] speakers and doesn't include native English, Hindi and Urdu language speakers.)</ref> | popplace = [[British Columbia]] • [[Ontario]] • [[Alberta]] | langs = [[Canadian English|English]] • [[Canadian French|French]] • [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] • [[Urdu]] • [[Hindi]] | rels = [[Sikhism]] • [[Hinduism]] • [[Christianity]] • [[Islam]] • [[Irreligion|Non-religious]] | related = [[Indian Canadians]] • [[Pakistani Canadians]] • [[Punjabi Americans]] }}
'''Punjabi Canadians''' are [[Canadians|Canadian citizens]] whose heritage originates wholly or partly in the [[Punjab]], a region in northern [[South Asia]], which encompasses [[India]] and [[Pakistan]]. There are large Punjabi communities in [[British Columbia]], concentrated in [[Surrey, BC|Surrey]], and in [[Brampton, Ontario|Brampton]], a city in the [[Greater Toronto Area]] of [[Ontario]].
{{Punjabis}}
==History== By 1906, there were 1,500 [[Sikh]] workers living in Canada, almost entirely from the [[Punjab]]. Punjabis avoided the [[Anti-Oriental Riots of 1907]] by staying indoors.<ref>[http://sikhs.org/100th/part1a.html Century of Struggle and Success The Sikh Canadian Experience] 13 November 2006</ref>
Punjabi Canadians began occupying all areas of Vancouver in the 1960s, however two concentrations developed: South Vancouver and Burnaby;<ref name=NayarSikhdiasporap327>Nayar, ''[[The Sikh Diaspora in Vancouver]]'', p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=NShXfaNbRyEC&pg=PA327 327].</ref> it was at this time that the [[Punjabi Market (Vancouver)|Punjabi Market]], located in South Vancouver, was founded. Later in the 1970s, Punjabi populations began appearing in [[Delta, British Columbia|Delta]], [[Richmond, British Columbia|Richmond]], and [[Surrey, British Columbia|Surrey]]. Vandalism against houses owned by Indo-Canadians and a Sikh [[gurdwara]] occurred in the 1970s, especially in 1974-1975 in Richmond.<ref name=JohnstonHughp7>Johnston, Hugh, p. 7.</ref>
==Distribution== In [[Metro Vancouver]], 5.5% of residents reported speaking [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] at home, as of 2011. 21.3% of [[Surrey, BC|Surrey]] residents speak it as their primary language at home. In [[Ontario]], Punjabi Canadians are prevalent in the [[Greater Toronto Area]], especially in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]], [[Markham, Ontario|Markham]], [[Mississauga]], [[Brampton]], and [[Ajax, Ontario|Ajax]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vancouversun.com/news/metro/census+punjabi+speaking+population+growing+metro+vancouver/7440097/story.html|title=Census: Punjabi-speaking population growing in Metro Vancouver|publisher=[[Vancouver Sun]]|date=October 24, 2012}}</ref>
Punjabi is the third most spoken language of the [[Parliament of Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/world/oye-hoye-punjabi-is-now-the-third-language-in-parliament-of-canada-2493038.html|title=Oye hoye! Punjabi is now the third language in Parliament of Canada|author=Firstpost|date=3 November 2015|work=Firstpost}}</ref>
==Religion== During the early stages of Punjabi immigration to Canada, most pioneers were of the Sikh faith.<ref>Nayar, ''[[The Punjabis in British Columbia]]'', p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=q7pO-IZY218C&pg=PA9 9]. "It is interesting to note that, in the BC Lower Mainland (Vancouver and surrounding municipalities, including Burnaby, New Westminster, Richmond, and Surrey), Sikhs raised outside the Punjab refer to themselves as Punjabi and use the term interchangeably with "Sikh," understanding the two as synonymous."</ref> Today, Punjabi Canadians remain mostly Sikh, however also include large numbers of [[Muslims]] and smaller numbers of [[Hindus]] and [[Christians]].
